        <mxCell id="g2l74eIDyHNDRNg9rZEy-103" parent="1" style="text;whiteSpace=wrap;" value="Main Interactions&#xa;&#xa;1. User accesses the web application from the Internet. The request enters the custom VPC through the Internet Gateway and reaches the public Application Load Balancer endpoint.&#xa;&#xa;2. Web Application Server stores the uploaded PDF file in Amazon S3.&#xa;&#xa;3. Web Application Server writes document metadata and initial processing status to Amazon RDS.&#xa;&#xa;4. Web Application Server publishes a document-uploaded event to Amazon SNS.&#xa;&#xa;5. Amazon SNS fans out the event to two Amazon SQS queues: one for fixed-size chunking and one for paragraph-aware chunking.&#xa;&#xa;6. Worker processes poll the corresponding Amazon SQS queues and receive processing jobs.&#xa;&#xa;7. Worker processes write generated chunks, processing statistics, and updated processing status to Amazon RDS.&#xa;&#xa;8. Web Application Server retrieves processing status, generated chunks, and comparison results from Amazon RDS.&#xa;&#xa;9. The Application Load Balancer forwards the HTTP request to the Web Application Server running on an EC2 instance managed by the Auto Scaling Group in the private subnet. The Web Server is not directly exposed to the Internet.&#xa;&#xa;NAT Gateway note:&#xa;The NAT Gateway provides outbound Internet access for EC2 instances in private subnets, allowing them to access AWS public service endpoints such as Amazon S3, SNS, and SQS, as well as software package repositories. It is not part of the public inbound request path." vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="460" width="560" x="1080" y="80" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
      </root>
